│ which means \"if we can prove the sign bit is 0 (positive)\", then return   │
│ the operand as-is. However, this check is flawed for select instructions    │
│ where one branch can be negative.\n\nThe problem is that                    │
│ `computeKnownFPSignBit` is being called on the select instruction `%sel =   │
│ select i1 %cmp, half %x, half 0xH0000`. The analysis incorrectly concludes  │
│ that the sign bit is known to be 0 (positive). This happens because:\n- The │
│ condition `%cmp = fcmp ogt half %abs1, 0xH0000` compares `fabs(x)` with     │
│ 0.0\n- When `fabs(x) > 0.0`, it means `x` is non-zero, so the select        │
│ chooses `%x`\n- When `fabs(x) <= 0.0`, it means `x` is zero (including      │
│ -0.0), so the select chooses `0.0`\n\nHowever, the analysis fails to        │
│ account for the fact that when `x` is a negative non-zero value (like       │
│ -0.000000059604), `fabs(x) > 0.0` is true, so the select returns the        │
│ negative `x`, which has a sign bit of 1. The current logic incorrectly      │
│ assumes that because one branch is positive (0.0) and the condition         │
│ involves `fabs`, the result must be positive.\n\n4. Proposed Edit           │
│ Point(s):\n+ The issue is in the fabs simplification logic in               │
│ `llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp` at line 6307. The current check │
│ `if (computeKnownFPSignBit(Op0, Q) == false)` is too aggressive for select  │
│ instructions where the true value can be negative. We need to ensure that   │
│ we only eliminate the fabs when we can truly prove the operand is           │
│ non-negative.\n\n5. Conclusion: The fix involves being more conservative in │
│ the fabs simplification. Instead of just checking if the sign bit is known  │
│ to be 0, we should verify that the value cannot be negative. This will      │
│ prevent the incorrect elimination of fabs calls on select instructions that │
│ can return negative values."})                                              │
